logs.text:
I'm going to come at this from a different angle, and I may take a while to get to the point, so bear with me.

&amp;#x200B;

I took my sister to see Fellowship of the Ring in the theater when it came out, and she complained the whole time about how white it was.  In fact, when Aragorn made his speech to Boromir about how he would "defend the white city," she leaned over to me and whispered "yeah, you and David Duke."  I was *so mad* at her because 1) I had been waiting for this movie for a long time and wanted to enjoy it, and 2) her primary argument was that this is fantasy, so you can do anything you want, including have black hobbits.

&amp;#x200B;

Now, there is undoubtedly plenty of racist stuff in LotR, but this always struck me as the argument of someone who didn't take the fantasy genre seriously.  The idea that fantasy means you can do "whatever you want" without regard for creating a coherent world is just not true.  Even though it is fantasy, Tolkien was trying to evoke a particular time and place that, due to geography and technology, would likely be ethnically homogenous.  The idea of cosmopolitan towns where a wide variety of races/cultures/religions/etc. were represented seems like a very modern idea that is anachronistic in a proto (or quasi, or semi) medieval world.

&amp;#x200B;

Over the years, I've gradually changed my opinion on this for a couple of reasons.  The first, and most important, is that medieval Europe had a lot more ethnic representation than I would have thought before looking into it.  There are a ton of great sources out there, but suffice to say that if you google "black people in medieval Europe" you'll find no shortage of reading material.  I'll also add that one of the reasons we tend to think of these societies as so white has to do with a little something called "black erasure," but that's a more controversial topic... I'll just say do a google image search for Titus Kaphar to see some interesting art.  In short, there are plenty of valid reasons to include non-white people in your medieval Europe-inspired fantasy, especially if your story focuses on the class of people who can afford to travel regularly.

&amp;#x200B;

The second reason is a little more abstract, but it has to do with art and the idea of adaptation.  Adaptation is always a struggle of staying "true to the source material" vs adapting the story for your current audience.  We have a choice in the material we choose to adapt, and if an artist chooses to adapt an all-white story, they either need to update that story to reflect the more modern, racially diverse world we live in, or they need to have a good answer for why this story needed to be 100% white.  Claiming "well that's the way it was in the book" is just not a valid defense for someone creating an adaptation in 2018, especially in the context of an entertainment industry that has only recently started reflecting the diversity of its audience.  

&amp;#x200B;

So, the most reasonable path is to find ways to include diversity that make sense for your story.  You mention Black Panther, but that movie still found a way to include lots of white people.  If every single person in the movie had been black, it would have seemed weird, and the only reason we don't feel that way about movies that are all white is that white is still seen as the default.

&amp;#x200B;

Long story short, I think it is much more important that a black Polish person today (and there are a few, and don't google "black poles," I found that out the hard way) feel that they are visible in the country's biggest cultural export than it is to maintain 100% fidelity to the source.

&amp;#x200B;

More importantly, though, there's a ton of speculation here on how Ciri's ethnicity will be explained, but  *no one actually knows yet*, so it's impossible to say if that reason is inconsistent with the logic of the story world (which I still think would be a valid complaint).  The only objection that anyone can reasonably have right now is that black and Polish are somehow incompatible, which just isn't true, no matter what time period you are looking at.
